        <p>G color – this color is one of the most popular color of choice because it knocks on the door of the colorless family standing right outside the spectrum. A G color graded diamond will have no noticeable color to the untrained eye and only the slightest trace of tint can be detected when compared to higher color grades.</p>
        <p>H color – for a lot of people, H color seems to be the minimum threshold for a diamond to be considered having “no obvious color.” H color exhibits only a very subtle hint of color when compared side by side with higher color grades. G and H are often grouped together. Most people are typically okay with either one, although some state they’d prefer G “just to play it safe.” Both of these colors are perfect options in my opinion and I don’t think you can go wrong with either one. When I compared G color to H, I could not see a visible difference. G-H seems to be the sweet spot for the most consumers.</p>
        <p>I color – This is typically about where, on the color scale, the hint of yellow starts to become apparent to the naked eye. A subtle hue of color is detectable when the diamond is viewed carefully and on its side under the right lighting conditions (Shown in the next photo below). I color provides a lot of value without compromising much and is often the #1 color of choice when you want to get a larger diamond as they become more affordable. If you’re willing to compromise slightly on color to obtain a larger diamond, I color could be for you. I color is one of my personal favorites.</p>
        <p>J color – the last color in the “colorless” family.  We have to remind ourselves, that it is still considered “near colorless”  and through our own tests and research we would definitely consider it near colorless. A hint of color is detectable when viewed loose on its own and it becomes a tad more obvious when compared to higher color grades. J color is another great choice if you want a larger diamond for the budget.</p>


        <h2>K, L, M</h2>
        <p>K-L-M are grouped together in the “faint yellow” family. It is actually fairly tricky to differentiate the three colors in this group, but with some patience and careful attention and of course the right lighting the average person can put them in the right order by detecting the slight variations in color. </p>

